text.Taxonomy and naming:
Eucalyptus capillosa was first formally described by the botanists Ian Brooker and Stephen Hopper in 1991 from a specimen near Merredin and the description was published in the journal Nuytsia. The specific epithet (capillosa) is a Latin word meaning "hairy", referring to the hairy seedlings.Brooker and Hopper described two subspecies that have been accepted by the Australian Plant Census:

Eucalyptus capillosa subsp. capillosa is a small to medium-sized tree;
Eucalyptus capillosa subsp. polyclada is a mallee to 6 m (20 ft).The name polyclada is derived from the Ancient Greek words polys meaning "many" and klados meaning "branch", "twig" or "stem", referring to the mallee habit of this subspecies.
